      "id": "ffb5b794b0eab4f1",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "ffb5b794b0eab4f1",
        "text": "They are supposed to motivate the acceptance of a communication by giving a speechless understanding of how a certain communication is meant. In Lubmann's words: they motivate by increased selectivity. In this version his thesis is at least genetically problematic. For it is questionable whether the fact that something works – one pays with money, for example – can be regarded as a sufficient reason for a new communication technique to become established. He does state this fact when, following Gehlen, he declares all communication to be improbable, but he leaves it unclear what special properties of the media, if not their sheer bookability, are supposed to help overcome this improbability. The problem, technically speaking, is how the binary schematized media codes (for reasons of \"presumptive completeness\" of the options they denote) – \"true or false\" for science, \"strong or weak\" for politics, \"you and no one else\" in the case of love, and \"to have or not to have\" in the field of economics – can be asymmetrized to such an extent that structurally one of the two options is given preference. Only when true statements are systematically linked to true statements, science comes into being; only when power does not give itself away, but tries to maintain and increase, it becomes politics; only when one does not orientate one's actions on this or that experience, but on the experience of another, one can speak of love; and only when, as one has to say with regard to the second coding of property by money, payments follow payments or at least payments keep the upper hand over non-payments, it comes to the differentiation of an economic system. "
